-- Brown University's Investments Gain 10% to Beat Yale, Trail Harvard Funds
-- B y   G i l l i a n   W e e
-- 2010-10-04T20:43:17Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-04/brown-university-investments-gain-10-in-year-to-beat-yale-trail-harvard.html
Brown University’s investments rose
10 percent in the year ended June 30, beating the 8.9 percent
return of Yale University and trailing the 11 percent gain of
Harvard University.  The fund was valued at $2.18 billion as of June, the
Providence, Rhode Island, school said in an e-mailed statement
on Oct. 2. The endowment received more than $135.3 million in
gifts in the past year, Sarah Kidwell, a Brown spokeswoman, said
today in an e-mail.  Brown generated an average annual return of 4.6 percent in
the five years through June and a 6.2 percent gain over the past
decade, compared with the 4.7 percent and 7 percent increases of
Harvard, the Cambridge, Massachusetts, school with $27.4
billion. Yale, the New Haven, Connecticut, university with $16.7
billion, reported the worst performance among Ivy League schools
that have announced results. Princeton University plans to
announce its fund’s performance later this month.  Pensions, endowments and other institutional funds returned
a median of 13 percent in the past year, 3.1 percent for the
past five years and 3.4 percent in the past decade, according to
Wilshire Associates, a consulting firm in Santa Monica,
California. The  Standard & Poor’s 500 Index  of stocks rose 12
percent in the year ended June 30.  The Ivy League consists of eight private schools in the
northeastern U.S. Columbia University’s $6.5 billion endowment
jumped 17 percent in the past year, while the University of
Pennsylvania’s $5.7 billion fund gained 13 percent. Dartmouth
College reported a 10 percent return for its $3 billion fund.
Cornell University said its $4.4 billion in investments rose 13
percent.  Below is a list of endowment results for selected schools.  To contact the reporter on this story:
